					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I see how some things don't need to be updated every frame, but those things are usually game mechanics, such as your character's health. That doesn't need to be so immediate and constant. But the things that matter really should be done every frame. Cutting your frame rate in half is a big deal to me. Have any of you played Bugs Bunny's Birthday Blowout? Everyone that has ever played that game knows that it has a terrible framerate (I still love that game though). It's really important that sprites and scrolling are updated every frame. 
<br />
<br />It's funny how those things take up so much time. I counted the cycles of my scrolling/updating routine, and I like to overestimate, so I assume that every instruction takes 5 cycles. It took about 2300 cycles with that assumption, so it takes a couple hundred less cycles than that, but it's still a lot. That does deal with scrolling, updating the name table, and attribute table correctly.
<br />
<br />I suppose there is quite a bit of time left in each frame. I don't think it's impossible to have the game run at 60hz.</div>

